<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / World Stock Markets: Indian GDRs firm despite cancellation
of VSNL
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BOMBAY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
India's overseas listed shares have been supported over the last few days by
institutional buying which had been set aside for the cancelled Dollars 1bn
Euro-issue by VSNL, the overseas telecommunications group, Reuter reports
from Bombay.
Analysts said that most Indian global depositary receipts (GDRs) -
certificates representing domestic shares - had risen by between 10 to 20
per cent since last Friday.
However, this follows a sharp decline in their value since February when
many of the world's emerging stock markets fell back after the US lifted
interest rates.
Mr Ajit Dayal of Jardine Fleming India Securities said: 'Fund managers who
have India-demarcated cash are buying those shares (GDRs). They are watching
good corporate results and generally good economic fundamentals.'
Twenty-two Indian companies have issued GDRs over the last three years,
raising nearly Dollars 2bn from international markets.
VSNL's Euro-issue, which would have been India's biggest, was abruptly
withdrawn last week after fund managers balked at the high price set by the
government.
The domestic stock market has also been resilient over the past week:
Bombay's BSE index yesterday added 10.70 at 3,769.72, after a 40-point
advance on Monday.
</TEXT>
