<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / International Company News: Parent to boost capital of CS
First Boston by Dollars 400m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CS Holding, the Swiss financial group, confirmed yesterday its plans to
provide its US-based investment banking subsidiary, CS First Boston, with a
capital infusion of about Dollars 400m.
The move is being made in an effort to boost CS First Boston's earning
power.
Mr Gerhard Beindorff, a spokesman for CS Holding, said yesterday that work
on an equity capital increase for CS First Boston of about Dollars 400m was
at 'an advanced stage'.
It will be the second large infusion of capital at CS First Boston in four
years. In 1990, its parent provided Dollars 300m in equity capital as part
of an Dollars 800m recapitalisation plan aimed at restoring confidence in
the bank, which was struggling at the time under the weight of troubled
loans.
When this latest infusion is completed, probably at some point in this
quarter, CS First Boston will have capital of Dollars 1.7bn. This is still
relatively small by the standards of its biggest Wall Street rivals such as
Salomon Brothers (Dollars 5.3bn in capital), Goldman Sachs (Dollars 5bn) and
Morgan Stanley (Dollars 4.5bn).
Equity capital is crucial for investment banks. The larger their capital
base, the more they can use their own money in the financial markets for
proprietary trading and underwriting activities, and the more likely they
are to earn a high credit rating which allows them to conduct derivatives
business with clients.
In recent years, a large share of investment banks' profits have come from
capital- intensive businesses such as proprietary derivatives trading.
The decision to provide the capital infusion comes a month after CS Holding
increased its stake in CS First Boston from 68.5 per cent to 75.7 per cent
by purchasing the stakes of five foreign institutional shareholders.
</TEXT>
