<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / International Company News: Electrolux plans global share
offering in Autoliv
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Electrolux, the world's leading maker of household appliances, yesterday
stepped up its refocusing programme by launching a global offering of 25m
shares in Autoliv, Europe's leading supplier of car safety equipment.
The move could raise up to SKr4.5bn (Dollars 584m) and produce a capital
gain of more than SKr3bn.
Mr Lennart Ribohn, Electrolux senior executive vice-president, said the sale
would improve the company's opportunities to expand core activities in east
Asian, South American and east European markets. Proceeds will also help
fund the group's just-finalised DM730m (Dollars 439.7m) purchase of
Hausgerate, AEG's household appliance unit.
Autoliv has 40 per cent of the European market in car safety equipment such
as seatbelts, airbags and child restraint seats. Growth has been rapid, in
spite of the car industry recession, due to rising demand for airbags and
increased emphasis on safety.
Last year, Autoliv's sales climbed to SKr5.33bn from SKr3.53bn, and
operating income rose to SKr310m from SKr211m. Progress continued in the
first quarter of 1994, with sales rising 69 per cent, to SKr2.0bn, and
operating income more than doubling to SKr99m from SKr45m. The book value of
the company, which Electrolux bought in 1980 as part of a larger purchase,
is around SKr1.3bn.
The issue will have three tranches. The biggest, 8.75m shares, will be
allocated to Swedish institutional and retail investors. The balance will be
split equally between the US and international markets. Enskilda Corporate,
Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken and Merrill Lynch International are the joint
global co-ordinators of the issue.
Shares are to be sold to institutions for between SKr160 and SKr180 each,
following a book-building exercise. Swedish retail investors, who are
expected to buy about 5 per cent of the company, will be offered a
SKr9-per-share discount.
Selling Autoliv enables Electrolux to fund the Hausgerate purchase without a
rights issue.
</TEXT>
