<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Royal Bank of Scotland seeks to purchase building society
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Royal Bank of Scotland would like to buy a medium-sized building society
with a 'recognisable name' in the high street, Mr George Mathewson, its
chief executive said yesterday.
Mr Mathewson, whose bank will disclose its interim results for the six
months to March 31 today, said a society acquisition could help it with its
strategy of diversifying business, and making its earnings less volatile.
Mr Mathewson confirmed Royal Bank had been interested in acquiring
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building Society, for which Lloyds has bid Pounds
1.8bn. But it was also interested in societies with a different mix of
operations. 'We would certainly be interested in the right building society.
It would need to be substantial in size, of high quality, and with a
recognisable brand name,' he said.
Mr Mathewson said that the acquisition of a society could also help to
strengthen its deposit base. 'The cost-income ratios of other societies may
be higher (than C&amp;G's) but that does not necessarily mean they are poorer
businesses,' he said.
He also said that Royal Bank might be an attractive owner for a society
because it had shown it was capable of allowing subsidiaries such as Direct
Line, its telephone insurance arm, to have operating autonomy.
Mr Mathewson's confirmation of interest in acquiring a society follows
similar statements by Bank of Scotland, Abbey National and TSB Group.
Mr Mathewson said that Royal Bank would like to increase the proportion of
residential mortgages within its assets because they have been less risky
than corporate loans. This would help to make its earnings less volatile.
Background, Page 28
</TEXT>
