<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Euro-market benefits 'confirmed'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The European single-market trading system has left the logistic departments
of many UK businesses celebrating as they benefit from better trade
structures, but drawn fire from finance directors who face a new accounting
headache.
That is the message of a study released yesterday by the Customs and Excise
board on the impact of the removal of community trade barriers on British
companies. It comes at the end of the first full year of using the new
trading and European Union statistical system, known as Intrastat.
The study, based on a survey of 1,000 companies, reaffirms the department's
earlier prediction that British business should reap at least Pounds 440m
worth of benefit from the single market over the next five years - although
it admits that many business people remain unconvinced about these gains.
This savings figure is calculated through a 'cost/benefit' balance sheet
which measures the impact of switching to the new regime.
On the 'benefit' side, Customs calculates that last year companies saved
about Pounds 151.97m because they no longer had to declare exports and
imports at ports. They also saved Pounds 5.83m from cheaper community
transit costs and Pounds 3.99m from the simpler VAT system.
On the 'cost' side, companies faced Pounds 97.33m start-up costs switching
to the new system, which requires any company with an EU trade balance of
more than Pounds 135,000 to submit trade statistics from in-house trading
data.
They also faced Pounds 3.99m of extra annual operating costs from the new
system for value added tax returns.
However, annual operating costs of the new system were only Pounds 40.44m a
year - which implies an annual saving of Pounds 134.98m to UK business as a
whole after initial start-up costs.
But in spite of the department's up-beat conclusion, it faces a difficult
public relations job in getting this message across to business, Mr Mark
Eland, Customs commissioner, admitted yesterday.
Part of the problem, he said, was that the new system had created another
accounting headache for company finance departments - even where the same
company had benefitted through more efficient trade structures.
Bigger companies have, unsurprisingly, born the brunt of the costs of
Intrastat. Although the average switch-over cost for the 25,000 UK trading
companies in the survey was calculated to be only Pounds 1,608, one large
company quoted a cost of Pounds 1m. Smaller companies quoted start-up costs
below predictions. The smallest trading companies have arguably seen the
best benefits because they no longer face the cost of reporting their
statistics at all.
Benefits have also varied between sectors. While transport reported savings
of 24 hours on road journeys to southern Europe, commodity trading groups
have been more critical. Companies carrying out chain transactions in oil,
for example, claim the system is penalising them because it fails to take
account of the complexities of multiple purchases.
</TEXT>
