<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Legal liaison plea at Iraq arms probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sensitive prosecutions brought by Customs and Excise would be improved if
the attorney-general had greater involvement in such cases, the chairman of
Customs told the Scott inquiry into the export of arms equipment to Iraq
yesterday.
Mrs Valerie Strachan, while not calling for changes to the independent
constitutional position occupied by Customs, said that there would be
benefits in more regular meetings between its lawyers and the attorney over
such prosecutions.
Improved contact would bring Customs into line with the director of public
prosecutions and the Serious Fraud Office, whose lawyers regularly meet the
attorney-general as a matter of course.
It would lessen the chances of Customs getting 'out of line' with the
prosecution policies of the director of public prosecutions and the Serious
Fraud Office, and help the attorney-general carry out his role as overall
supervisor of Customs as well as answer questions about its operations, she
said.
She added: 'I would see positive advantages from a number of points of view
of the relationship being a bit closer, better articulated and with a more
regular channel of communication.'
Observer, Page 25
