<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Pay offer of 2.2% for civil servants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Members of the CPSA, the biggest civil service union, are being urged by
their executive to accept a pay offer worth 2.2 per cent in one of the first
negotiated public-sector pay deals this year after the government's pay-bill
freeze.
The Treasury said the rise for about 100,000 typists, secretaries and
clerical workers across the civil service would be wholly funded by
efficiency savings in line with government policy.
Greater flexibility in pay negotiations has been created by the relaxation
of rules preventing departmental cost savings from being carried over from
one financial year into the next.
Mr Barry Reamsbottom, CPSA general secretary, said: 'Against the background
of the government's determination to freeze the public-sector pay bill, this
is a remarkable achievement. We have forced the government to make a decent
offer.'
Most of the rise involves a one-off lump sum payment of 1.8 per cent which
will not be consolidated into pay or pensions. The rest comprises
performance pay.
The deal looks like setting the trend for public-sector settlements this
year. Most forecasts give overall rises of between 2 per cent and 3 per cent
in the public sector.
The union also said that it had recorded its highest membership for a decade
in spite of legislation aimed at making it easier for union members to
relinquish their memberships.
</TEXT>
