<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Builders launch Brussels lobby group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An organisation to win Britain a bigger share of the European Commission's
Pounds 8.5bn research and development budget was launched yesterday by the
construction industry.
The Construction Industry European Research Club, which is supported by the
Department of the Environment, will provide information on impending
projects, arrange partnerships with other European companies and research
organisations, provide contacts and prepare submissions to the Commission.
It will be managed by the independent Building Research Establishment, which
has extensive contacts with research organisations in continental Europe.
To qualify for EU funds applications must be supported by bodies from at
least two EU countries. Establishing co-operative ventures between UK
companies competing in the same sector, and arranging cross-border support
has proved difficult in the past.
British companies have failed to win as big a share of the EU budget as they
would like. There was now a significant opportunity to redress this balance,
said Mr Tony Baldry, the construction minister.
Corporate membership will cost Pounds 1,000 a year and Pounds 500 for
academic organisations.
Builders started work on 48,800 homes in Britain during the three months to
the end of March, 1 per cent more than during the corresponding period last
year. Starts were also 1 per cent higher than during the previous three
months, figures published yesterday by the environment department show.
</TEXT>
