<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Fears of Rosyth closure are renewed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fears that the closure of Rosyth naval base will be announced when the
outcome of the latest defence expenditure review is revealed in July were
heightened by government ministers yesterday.
Mr Jonathan Aitken, minister for defence procurement, told MPs in the
Commons that while the Royal Navy now had fewer ships, there had been no
corresponding reduction in the support facilities provided by four separate
bases.
He said: 'We will have to look carefully at the size of the infrastructure
as well as at the size of the fleet.'
Mr Aitken accused Labour MPs of seeking to exaggerate 'promises which were
never made' by Mr John Major, the prime minister. Mr Aitken said assurances
given by the prime minister that the employment implications of closing the
Rosyth base in Fife would be taken into account fell short of the kind of
promise which Labour MPs inferred he had made.
Mr John Reid, a Labour defence spokesman, called for an assurance that
before any decision was announced all the alternative costs would be made
available to MPs.
Mr Aitken said Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, would be among ministers
consulted before any final decision was taken. After the proposals were
announced the government would publish the information on which decisions
had been based.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, reaffirmed that the government
had no intention of making any further reduction in the 'fighting capability
of our forces'.
</TEXT>
