<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Commons backs Sunday betting on horse racing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sunday horse racing with betting on- and off-course was overwhelmingly
approved by the Commons last night as the government backed down over plans
to abolish market franchise rights.
A MPs voted by a majority of 101 to allow Sunday betting as part of the
government's de-regulation bill.
It brings England and Wales into line with other horse racing nations such
as Ireland, France and Italy, which already allow Sunday betting.
Mr Neil Hamilton, trade and industry minister, said: 'I cannot myself see
that as a result of the changes proposed here, which I warmly support, the
nation will suddenly be plunged into a hell-hole of gambling the like of
which we have never seen before.'
If the Lords back the change, the British Horse Racing Board will include in
its fixture list a small number of Sundays in the next two years.
The government was later forced to withdraw proposals to de-regulate the law
under which local authorities holding market franchise rights can oppose the
creation of rival markets - such as weekly open-air markets - nearby.
Threatened with a backbench revolt, Mr Tim Sainsbury, trade and industry
minister, said that the government would now 'discuss with all interested
parties how best to remove the adverse effects of market franchise monopoly
rights'.
Sir Michael Neubert, Conservative MP for Romford, said the market franchise
rights were 'an effective means of controlling markets, which has ensured
that markets have prospered up and down the country'.
Ministers plan to bring forward amendments 'on an agreed basis' when the
de-regulation bill reaches the Lords.
Labour voiced worries about the potential impact of the bill on health and
safety standards. Mr Derek Fatchett, Labour's trade and industry spokesman,
called for this issue to be cut out of the legislation.
He said he feared that ministers would phase out important safety
regulations using the 'excessive powers' given to them under the bill to
repeal measures without primary legislation.
Mr Hamilton stressed the need to avoid imposing unnecessary costs on
business.
</TEXT>
