<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Environment failures rapped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government has failed to keep more than 27 environmental commitments,
according to the annual audit of its environmental performance published
yesterday.
The count does not include some of the slippages in policy implementation
for which the government has been most heavily criticised.
Environmentalists yesterday attacked the government's failure to develop an
underground store for nuclear waste, and the lack of finance for the newly
created Energy Saving Trust, which is intended to promote energy efficiency.
The 200-page report lists the action taken on 657 separate environmental
commitments. The report is the third annual assessment of This Common
Inheritance, the government's environmental strategy published in 1990.
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, said yesterday that there had
been action 'on almost all commitments'. While the government was determined
to maintain high environmental standards this could be achieved within the
framework of competitiveness and by reducing regulation. The National Audit
Office yesterday criticised English Nature, the government-funded
conservation body, for its management of England's 3,700 sites of special
scientific interest. It said many reserves were hard to find and few were
signposted.
This Common Inheritance - The Third Year Report. HMSO. Pounds 21. Protecting
and Managing Sites of Special Scientific Interest, HMSO Pounds 8.95.
</TEXT>
