FT  11 MAY 94 / Greens want Third World debt cancelled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Green party yesterday launched its European election manifesto, urging
the cancellation of most Third World debt and an end to the use of nuclear
power.
The manifesto combines the Green antipathy to free trade with a call for
European Union membership to be open to any country in Europe.
It spells out the party's opposition to the European single market and the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. The Greens believe the agreements
'undermine local economic initiatives and environmental standards'. They are
also opposed to a single European currency.
In the last European election, in 1989, the Greens gained 14.9 per cent of
the vote.
Plaid Cymru, the Welsh nationalist party, calls in its manifesto for reform
of the Common Agricultural Policy and for British acceptance of the
Maastricht treaty's social chapter.
Mr Dafydd Wigley, party leader, said subsidiarity was 'equally applicable to
the relationship between Cardiff and London as it is to the case of London
and Brussels'.
Green Vision for Europe. 10 Station Parade, Balham High Road, London SW12
9AZ. Making Europe Work for Wales. Plaid Cymru, 51 Cathedral Road, Cardiff.
Pounds 1.95.
</TEXT>
