<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Rightwing MPs divided over Major's future
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A split has emerged among rightwing Conservative MPs over how to get the
party to adopt their agenda. They are divided between those who want Mr John
Major to go and those who think sustaining him in office is their best
course of action.
The split suggests that all may not yet be lost for the prime minister even
if the Tory party does badly in next month's European elections as indicated
in the latest Guardian/ICM poll. The poll puts the Conservatives 17 points
behind, excluding 'don't knows', with Labour on 44 per cent, the Tories on
27 per cent and the Liberal Democrats on 24 per cent.
The rightwing Tory split stems partly from a feeling that Mr Michael
Portillo - the Thatcherite chief Treasury secretary who is the preferred
candidate of many of the right - would be unlikely to beat Mr Michael
Heseltine if a leadership contest were staged later this year.
However, some rightwingers believe there is a case for a change of leader
even if this makes the pro-European Mr Heseltine prime minister. Encouraged
by Mr Heseltine's voting record on issues such as the age of consent for
homosexuals, they argue that on many subjects he is closer to the right of
the party than the left. If he came out in favour of a referendum on the
next step of European integration they say they would warm towards him
further.
A number of rightwingers supported Mr Heseltine against Mr Major and Mr
Douglas Hurd in the last Tory leadership contest in 1990.
MPs in this category include Mr John Carlisle, MP for Luton North who
recently said he was ready to stand in an autumn leadership contest; Mr Tony
Marlow, MP for Northampton North who stunned the Commons in March by
demanding Mr Major's resignation; Sir Peter Tapsell, the Euro-sceptic MP for
Lindsey East; and Mr David Evans, an executive of the Tory backbench 1922
Committee.
The second rightwing camp believes that a Heseltine premiership is to be
avoided at virtually any cost. As a leadership contest later this year is
therefore best avoided, they reason that their best bet is to promise Mr
Major their support while urging him to adopt more rightwing policies and to
appoint rightwingers to more prominent cabinet posts in a summer reshuffle.
Some of them think Mr Major could in effect be used as an interim leader
until Mr Portillo, or an alternative candidate from the right, is ready to
mount a winning challenge.
There is little or no enthusiasm among rightwingers for a prolonged Major
premiership as anything other than a means to an end. According to one MP:
'The big difference between now and 1990 is that no one is going around
saying this is a prime minister we have to go to the wall for.'
</TEXT>
