<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Stoy Hayward faces two probes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stoy Hayward, the accountancy firm, yesterday said it was to be the subject
of two high-profile professional investigations for its roles as auditor to
both Astra Holdings and Polly Peck International, Andrew Jack writes.
The details came after a day of confusion in which the joint disciplinary
scheme, the accountancy profession's senior regulatory body, delayed making
an official announcement.
Polly Peck, the conglomerate which entered administration in October 1990,
was controlled by Mr Asil Nadir, who fled to northern Cyprus while facing
charges of false accounting and theft involving Pounds 34m. Astra Holdings,
which was the subject of a highly critical and long-delayed Department of
Trade and Industry inspectors' report published last June, was a munitions
company connected to the Iraqi supergun affair. It is now in receivership.
Stoy Hayward was the principal auditor to both companies, although Polly
Peck's Cyprus subsidiaries were audited by Erdal &amp; Co, a local firm, and
other accounting services to the group and Mr Nadir were provided by Coopers
&amp; Lybrand.
A joint disciplinary scheme inquiry may focus on any chartered accountants
or accountancy firms associated with the companies under investigation,
including board members.
Stoy said it had been informed that the Institute of Chartered Accountants
in England and Wales had referred both cases to the scheme.
The scheme said it was delaying an announcement as a result of
'representations' after publicity concerning the Polly Peck investigation.
Mr Adrian Martin, Stoy's managing partner, said his firm had made no such
representations and he welcomed an independent review. He added: 'For a
regulatory system to be fair, it has to be open, consistently applied and
timely. This has not been the case.'
</TEXT>
