<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Lilley aims to ease fears over post offices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, will today unveil measures to
boost rural post offices in a move to ease backbenchers' fears over
proposals to privatise the Post Office.
In a speech to the Federation of Sub-Postmasters, which represents 19,000
sub-post offices, he will commit the government to strengthening the post
office network by making it easier to pay benefits across post office
counters.
The Department of Trade and Industry is still finalising its 22-month review
of the Post Office, which favours privatisation.
Mr Lilley, who is understood to favour the flotation of the Royal Mail, the
letters division, and Parcelforce, the parcels arm, will make it clear that
his reforms to post office counters will remain in place irrespective of the
government's review.
A significant number of Tory backbenchers oppose privatisation because of
the perceived threat to the rural post offices, many of which rely on a
subsidy from the Post Office.
Their fears were increased last year when Mr Lilley announced an expanded
range of benefits available for payment direct to bank and building society
accounts, which is seen as a threat to the post office network. However, the
government made clear that the system would not be made compulsory.
Mr Lilley will today attempt to assure both backbenchers and sub-postmasters
that there is no fear that large numbers of post offices face closure.
He has decided to make benefit payments through post offices more secure by
introducing three main reforms:
The use of bar codes on benefit books will be extended to clamp down on
fraud.
Computer terminals will be installed in post offices, to enable postmasters
to verify claimants. Benefit books will be replaced in the medium term with
special payment cards designed to cut theft and fraud.
Ministers believe Labour has mounted a 'scare campaign' about the threat of
automated credit transfer in its campaign against privatisation.
Mr Lilley intends to use his speech today to assure the postmasters that the
government needs the post office network to deliver benefits and that many
people would still prefer payment across the counter.
He is also known to support the DTI's favoured method of privatising the
Royal Mail and its parcels arm, which would leave Post Office Counters -
responsible for the sub-post offices - in the public sector.
His speech coincides with a campaign by Mr Bill Cockburn, Post Office chief
executive, to win over MPs to the merits of more commercialisation or
privatisation by stressing his commitment to the rural post offices.
</TEXT>
<XX>
