<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Convenience food set for bigger role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Convenience foods, private healthcare and home shopping are the sectors most
likely to benefit from further demographic and social changes before 2000,
according to Mintel.
Meanwhile, rock concerts, pub drinking and purchases of red meat are all set
for decline, says the report on consumer habits.
Three groups will make up a larger proportion of the population: families,
in particular those with children aged between five and 14; 'empty-nesters',
whose children have left home; and elderly people, especially those above
the age of 75.
For the food and drink markets, the ageing population and increase in
single-parent households - for whom time is at a premium - will mean the
increased use of convenience foods.
The decline in numbers of young people and increase in adults with young
children will lead to more home consumption of alcoholic drink and lower pub
attendance, says the report.
The increase in numbers of young children will have other consequences:
'Within the home, DIY activities will increase in popularity, as children
necessitate more decoration work.'
For the financial services market, there will be an overall growth in
segmentation between families and 'empty-nesters', the group forecasts.
It concludes: 'Consumers are likely to become more financially sophisticated
over the coming decade, with stocks and share ownership and unit-trust
ownership rising.
'Hand in hand with this will go a greater provision for personal pensions
and high-interest building society and bank accounts.'
</TEXT>
