<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Pressure grows on minister to resign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Nicholas Scott, the social security minister, was under growing pressure
to resign from the government last night after he admitted misleading the
Commons during a debate on rights for the disabled, James Blitz writes.
Following angry exchanges in the Commons, Mr John Smith, Labour leader,
called for Mr Scott's resignation after the minister admitted that his
department had helped Tory backbenchers to wreck the passage of a private
member's bill that would have required employers to provide facilities for
disabled people.
Mr Scott appeared determined to ride out allegations that he misled the
Commons last Friday when he stated that that his department had played no
part in drawing up the amendments.
Downing Street officials made clear that Mr Scott enjoyed the prime
minister's full confidence, and had cleared up any misunderstandings.
But Labour intensified pressure on the minister, seeing the row as a test of
the accountability of members of Mr John Major's government. In a letter to
the prime minister, Mr Smith said Mr Scott's statement was 'wholly
unsatisfactory'. He had 'confirmed that his department, with his authority,
had been involved in the preparation of the amendments'.
The Labour leader quoted a letter from the prime minister to a Labour MP, in
which Mr Major had said ministers should 'relinquish their positions' if
they knowingly failed to give truthful information the House.
Miss Betty Boothroyd, the Speaker, announced that she would rule soon on
whether Mr Scott had been in 'contempt' of the House.
</TEXT>
