<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Scottish Tories to confront leaders on election failure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Scottish Tories, chastened by their disastrous showing in last week's
regional council elections, will confront their leaders today at their
annual conference in Inverness.
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, will be the first of seven cabinet
ministers to address the conference. Mr John Major will attempt to rekindle
his premiership at the closing rally on Friday.
In a routine that has become all too familiar in the past decade of decline,
practically uninterrupted but for a revival in the 1992 general election,
the Scottish Tories will try to identify what changes of policy or
presentation to make.
The regional council election result, in which they made a net loss of 23
seats and took under 14 per cent of the vote, shocked them and came as a
pleasant surprise to their Scottish National party, Liberal Democrat and
Labour opponents.
The Tories are uncertain whether they lost support because of government
plans to take Scottish water out of local authority control, or whether
former supporters were expressing the same general discontent with the Major
government as their counterparts south of the border.
Mr Ian Lang, Scottish secretary, inclined to the latter interpretation,
although he also said the party would have to 'readdress the things we do
and the way in which we present them'. He does not believe many Tory
supporters thought it pointless to elect opposition-run councils which are
to be abolished in 1996 anyway.
Mr Hurd will tackle the issue of the hour when he winds up today's debate on
Europe, replying to a motion that 'supports the principle of subsidiarity,
rejecting the concept of a federal Europe'.
On Thursday Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, will reply to the debate on
the economy before embarking on two days of electioneering in north-east
Scotland for the European elections. Later that day Mr John McGregor, the
transport secretary, will speak.
Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, Mr Malcolm Rifkind,
defence secretary and Mr David Hunt, the employment minister will speak on
Friday.
</TEXT>
