<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Gummer joins attack on modern architecture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, launched a savage attack
yesterday on the standard of much modern architecture, echoing criticisms
repeatedly made by the Prince of Wales in recent years.
Speaking to the Cities 94 conference in London's Docklands, Mr Gummer
indicated he would use his planning powers to improve the quality of
buildings in British cities.
He made it clear he would block city-centre developments that he regarded as
poorly designed or out of keeping with existing buildings. He said: 'Too
many buildings which won prizes in the 1960s need to be pulled down in the
1990s.'
Mr Gummer gave as examples Birmingham's Bull Ring shopping centre, his own
departmental headquarters in Marsham Street in Westminster, and the National
Westminster Bank building in Leeds. He later added to the list residential
developments such as the high-rise flats overlooking Richmond Park at
Roehampton in south-west London. Many 1960s flats suffered from water
penetration, he added.
'One important quality of buildings is that they should keep the water out,'
he said. 'Many of the buildings of the 1960s are bad buildings in a
functional sense.'
Mr Gummer assured his audience that he was not against all modern
architecture. 'I certainly don't want pastiche styles,' he said. 'I want
buildings of today and tomorrow which respect what has gone before.'
He promised an initiative to set standards for developers, encouraging them
to create developments that complement existing buildings and specifying the
use of appropriate materials and finishes. 'This generation could be
remembered for architecture which enhanced its environment and used
imagination and innovation to build for the future by building to last,' he
said.
Architects and town planners welcomed Mr Gummer's plans.
'A lot of architects and planners were seduced by the new style of buildings
in the 1960s, and went too far,' said Mr Jed Griffiths, senior
vice-president of the Royal Town Planning Institute.
The Royal Institute of British Architects said it was 'delighted' at the new
emphasis on quality and design.
A new organisation to win Britain a bigger share of the European
Commission's Pounds 8.5bn research and development budget was launched
yesterday by the construction industry, Andrew Taylor writes.
The Construction Industry European Research Club, which is supported by the
environment department, will provide information on impending projects,
arrange partnerships with other European companies and research
organisations, and provide contacts and prepare submissions to the
commision.
</TEXT>
