<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / North Yemen leaders sack prime minister
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC WATKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SANAA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
North Yemen's political leaders yesterday stepped up their propaganda
offensive in the civil war by denouncing the prime minister, Mr Haydar Abu
Bakr al-Attas, and stripping him of all government powers.
Mr Attas is the fifth southerner dismissed in a week as northern political
leaders attempt to consolidate and legitimise their authority throughout the
country.
The military situation remained unclear, with each side broadcasting its own
version of events. Heavy fighting is reported around Aden, where northern
troops were said to have advanced to within three miles of the city on
Monday. But reports from Aden said the situation there was normal.
Northern troops appear to have secured the region around Lodah, about 100
miles to the north-east of Aden, and to have sent reinforcements on the road
to Ataq, 350 miles north-east of Aden, in anticipation of further fighting
there. Southern troops, reported to have taken heavy losses in last week's
fighting, are now regrouping to rebuff the expected northern advance.
So far, the main oilfields have been spared direct involvement in the
fighting. But observers say that could easily change as the battle unfolds
in and around Aden, the southern stronghold.
The north's main oilfields, which produce about 180,000 barrels a day, are
located at Mareb, 150 miles east of Sanaa. The south's main fields are in
the Hadramout Valley at Wadi Masila and produce 150,000 b/d. But oil men say
that between those fields 300 northern and southern tanks are now arrayed
against each other. If a battle should take place there, they admit, it
could mean one side or the other taking all the country's oil.
The dismissal of Mr Attas followed his appeal last week for outside forces
to help end the civil war, now in its second week. The Yemeni parliament,
meeting without its southern members, insisted that Mr Attas's actions were
illegal and notified embassies in Sanaa, the northern capital, that he no
longer represented the government.
The Sanaa government, which now describes itself as having the only
constitutional legitimacy in the country, has also sacked Mr Saleh Abu Bakr
bin-Husaynoon, oil minister.
</TEXT>
