<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Hata appeals for backing on problems ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata yesterday appealed for opposition
support to help his minority government tackle the host of urgent issues
ahead.
In his first policy speech, Mr Hata asked for co-operation in completing the
political reforms agreed in January, passing a budget for the current year,
reforming the tax system and in defusing trade tensions with the US. But the
two main opposition groups, the Liberal Democratic party and Social
Democratic party, were unimpressed.
Mr Hata's speech was 'void of substance', Mr Kiichi Miyazawa, former LDP
prime minister, said. Both parties are considering a no-confidence motion
soon after the budget is passed by the end of June.
Mr Hata apologised to neighbouring countries for the offence created by the
former justice minister's denial of an infamous wartime massacre. 'It is
regrettable such a situation arose,' he said.
'Japan's wartime aggression and colonial rule caused unbearable suffering
and sorrow for many people.'
Despite the unpromising outlook for his government, Mr Hata promised to
continue business as normally as possible. His administration would use
'plain language,' listen 'even more attentively to the opinions of both
ruling and opposition parties' and seek 'as wide an agreement as possible'.
The prime minister laid out a busy agenda, sticking to the policy accord
agreed by the coalition before the SDP's walk-out three weeks ago. He
planned 'as soon as possible' to enact a bill to redraw Japan's electoral
boundaries, the final stage of the switch from the current multi-seat
constituency system, blamed for fostering corruption, to a mix of single
seats and proportional representation.
The aim was to hold the next general election under the new system, likely
to be in place by late autumn. This could be optimistic, given the growing
pressure among SDP politicians for an early election under the existing
system, on the grounds the party might do better than under the new rules.
It is unclear, however, whether the Liberal Democratic party, the largest
opposition group, would similarly benefit. The SDP would need LDP help to
vote the government down.
Mr Hata said his administration aimed to produce draft tax reform plans in
June, the main point of which will be a cut in income tax, seen as essential
to stimulate the economy, and a rise in indirect taxes, anathema to the SDP.
Legislation is planned by the end of the year.
On trade, Mr Hata would strive to re-open economic framework talks with the
US, stalled since February. 'It is important to make efforts. . . toachieve
a phased reduction of the current account surplus,' including deregulation
and measures to stimulate domestic demand.
The cornerstone of foreign policy would continue to be the security treaty
with the US. Japan could no longer be a mere onlooker in international
affairs, Mr Hata added.
Mr Hata said Japan would continue to try to persuade North Korea, through
dialogue, to open all its suspected nuclear sites to international
inspection, but would respect any United Nations decision, a reference to
possible sanctions.
</TEXT>
