<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Berlusconi picks a safe economic team
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The economic team in the new Italian government led by Mr Silvio Berlusconi
has been the one area where all parties in the Freedom Alliance coalition
have found common ground.
This is less because the various members of the Alliance have identical
ideas on economic policy. Rather they were agreed on the type of
qualifications necessary for the three posts of the Treasury, finance
ministry and budget ministry.
Mr Berlusconi, as prime minister designate, found himself short of
experienced politicians in his own camp capable of handling these technical
portfolios. He also ran up against considerable reluctance among some of the
better known economists to enter a government that contained members of the
neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance.
He could have chosen his own economic adviser, Mr Antonio Martino, a
Chicago-trained economist teaching at the private Luiss University in Rome
and a committed free-marketeer. But Mr Berlusconi early on chose to place
him at the foreign ministry. Mr Berlusconi also approached Mr Piero
Barrucci, the outgoing minister, to stay on but the offer was turned down.
This left the field open for the top job of Treasury minister to Mr Lamberto
Dini, the 63-year-old director general of the Bank of Italy, with whom the
media magnate has been friendly for some time. The League initially raised
objections, claiming Mr Dini was too close to the discredited former
Christian Democrats. But these objections faded with the lack of a clear
alternative.
Mr Dini is well known internationally, having spent long years in the
International Monetary Fund. He is widely respected as having solid grasp of
both domestic and international monetary and financial issues, and is a
member of the European Union's monetary committee. Thus his appointment is a
clear signal to the financial markets that the new government will pursue a
sound economic policy, respecting the need to maintain tight budgetary
discipline.
By giving the main economic job to a non-politician in what is a political
cabinet - unlike the previous Amato and Ciampi governments - Mr Berlusconi
had to balance this with a politician in one of the other posts. With the
populist Northern League clamouring for recognition and sharing his
commitment to the free market, Mr Berlusconi has chosen Mr Giancarlo
Pagliarini, a League senator and a prominent accountant, as budget minister.
Mr Pagliarini, on the previous Senate's budget commission, is brimming with
energy and a fervent believer in deregulation and privatisation. The League
normally demands iron loyalty from its members and this may make it
difficult for him on occasions. But the League recognise him as their sole
expert on the economy and this should given him some margin of manoeuvre.
The difficulty of finding a finance minister from among the main Freedom
Alliance partners, led to the choice of Mr Giulio Tremonti, a former
Socialist tax expert who has just broken from the centrist Italian Pact of
Mr Mario Segni.
The major question now is whether Mr Dini will be treated by Mr Berlusconi
as a technician or as a key member of the cabinet taking the political
responsibility for economic policy. A secondary but important issue is the
fate of the team of Treasury officials built up over the past two years
under Mr Mario Draghi, the director-general. They have handled much of the
privatisation and also deal with all debt matters.
In private some at the Treasury have let it be known that they would find it
difficult to work with Mr Dini. At the same time members of the League and
the MSI have voiced concern at the power concentrated in Mr Draghi's hands.
However, Mr Dini would find it difficult to rebuild a new team quickly, and
Mr Berlusconi is anxious to move fast in the first 100 days.
Mr Dini's departure from the Bank of Italy also creates a potentially
awkward situation at the central bank both in terms of his replacement and
on the question of the institution's political independence. There is
already a precedent of former governor Guido Carli being Treasury minister.
But Mr Dini will now have to deal with Mr Antonio Fazio, the bank governor,
on policy issues when the two may not see eye to eye.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
               NEO-FASCISTS GIVEN TWO POSTS IN CABINET
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Five of the ministers in the government announced by the prime minister
designate Mr Silvio Berlusconi last night are from the far-right
National Alliance but only two are from the neo-fascist Italian Social
Movement (MSI), the core party of the National Alliance, and neither
was old enough to have been involved in the second world war. One of
them, 58-year-old MSI parliamentarian Giuseppe Tatarella, was named
posts minister and will also be one of two deputy prime ministers.
