<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 94 / Germans give credit warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Several leading German economic research institutes yesterday warned against
any further credits to Russia, saying economic collapse there was
accelerating, Reuter reports from Bonn.
Three leading think-tanks said in a report commissioned by the German
government that despite some progress the Russian reform process was not
working. Far-reaching structural changes in the country's economy were
needed, they said.
'Given the causes of the acceleration of the economic slowdown it appears
ill advised at the moment to put new financial means at Russia's disposal,'
said the report, from Berlin's DIW, the Kiel Institute for the World Economy
and the Halle institute. They said a complete collapse of industrial
production in Russia was possible and that mass unemployment was inevitable.
They advised the Russian government to scrap its current credit system and
to reduce subsidies. They recommended a 'realistic wage policy and the
closing of resource-wasting, loss-making businesses'. Germany has supplied
more than half of all western aid to the former Soviet Union but has
recently refused to give more export credits until Russia improves its
investor and trade protection laws.
Separately, however, the eastern Europe committee of the Federation of
German Industry (BDI) said it expected a further improvement in trade
between Russia and Germany if Moscow continued to invest in key sectors of
industry.
It said German imports from Russia had totalled DM10.7bn (Pounds 4.2bn) in
1993 and imports to Russia were DM11.4bn. 'Against the background of the
unfavourable economic developments in Russia in 1993 - a fall in GDP of 12
per cent, a 16 per cent decline in industrial production, inflation rates of
800 to 1,000 per cent - this development is encouraging,' the BDI said.
Declines in petrochemical, oil and gas production in Russia had not shown up
strongly so far in trade figures with Germany.
</TEXT>
